<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1867-11-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1867-11-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="443" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d443">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Burlingame</persName></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 224.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1867-11-11"><hi rend="italic">November</hi> 11, 1867.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your despatch, No. 145, of the 17th of
                            July last, upon the subject of a modification of the treaty between the
                            United States and China, has been received. The department sees no
                            objection to the proposed modification, but, before it can be formally
                            accepted by the President, it must be approved by the Senate. That body
                            will be consulted upon the subject early in the next session, and their
                            decision will be made known to you.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed>
                        </closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Anson Burlingame</hi>, Esq.,<hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>